Muircheartach’, a personal name meaning ‘sea-ruler’. In Scotland the name was often lenited to give   McCurdy  . Compare   Murdoch   and   Moriarty  . The name was also used to Anglicize <i>Mac Murchaidh</i> (see   McMorrow  )."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Mortimer was born in 1129, in Curry Mallet, Somerset, England as the daughter of Robert de Mortimer. She had at least 1 son with William Malet. She died in 1213, in Langport, Somerset, England, at the age of 84."},"et":{"1129–1213":"1129–1213","1125–1169":"1125–1169","1150–1194":"1150–1194","–Male":"Surnud","1129":"1129","Abt 1150":"umbes 1150","1169":"1169","1213":"1213","1125":"1125","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, England","Langport, Somerset, England":"Langport, Somerset, England"},"f